body: You have an opset-11 model. OnnxRuntime does not fully support opset-11 yet. It will only support opset-11 in its next release. Opset-10 models should run. Please try converting to opset-10 or wait for the next release in which opset-11 will be supported.

Actually keeping this opened for tracking.

CC: @askhade

Could you explain what you mean by your reply? The problem seems to be that mode='bilinear' is not supported. Changing opset_version does not seem to change this. If instead I change to mode='nearest' then it works.

Hello,

Your model was an opset-11 model and we had not completed the implementation for opset-11 Resize at that point. It is now supported via #2088 . Could you please re-build from master and give it a try ? Thanks.

```
/onnxruntime/onnxruntime/core/providers/cpu/tensor/upsample.h:228 void onnxruntime::UpsampleBase::ParseScalesData(const onnxruntime::Tensor*, std::vector<float>&) const scales_size > 0 was false. scales size should be greater than 0.
```
Its not working yet. U can try with demo code above. I'm not sure it is a bug in torch or onnxruntime. The scaling size is is not right.

@Godricly : There was a fix checked in for this yesterday night... can you try again...
Pytorch converters add empty scales as constant initializer and use sizes to set the output dimensions... there was a check missing for this which has now been checked in....

```
2019-10-23 15:10:48.572430561 [E:onnxruntime:, sequential_executor.cc:165 Execute] Non-zero status code returned while running Resize node. Name:'' Status Message: onnxruntime/onnxruntime/core/providers/cpu/tensor/upsample.h:221 void onnxruntime::UpsampleBase::ScalesValidation(const std::vector<float>&, onnxruntime::UpsampleMode) const scales.size() == 2 || (scales.size() == 4 && scales[0] == 1 && scales[1] == 1) was false. 'Linear' mode only support 2-D inputs ('Bilinear') or 4-D inputs with the corresponding outermost 2 scale values being 1 in the Resize operator
```
The session creation is passed.  But the execution is not working.
@askhade
it should be 50 before resize and 100 after resize In the demo code. You can debug with the code above.
Is there any update for this one?

I don't quite understand how you are constructing your onnx resize node from this :
ort_inputs = {ort_session.get_inputs()[0].name: dummy}
ort_outs = ort_session.run(None, ort_inputs)

To make this faster can you clarify what is the shape of your input, and what exactly is your scale?

For Linear mode we only support BiLinear meaning scale can be either [x, y] or [1, 1, x, y] 
This is the exact check which is failing so I suspect your scale does not conform to this...

I have no idea what you are asking for. Basically, I export the ONNX model of pytorch with bilinear mode interpolation. And those 2 lines has nothing to do with resize node at all. The input could be in any shape(100X100 is used here for demonstration). In the demo code, the input is downsampled with a stride of 2(50X50 now), which also is the input for the resize OP.  The expected output for resize is 100X100.
problem fixed with night build pytorch(1.4.0.dev20191103).

I can not export from PyTorch to ONNX using the upsample operator with torch version 1.3.1, 
onnx version 1.5.0.

MINIMUM CODE TO REPRODUCE:
```python
import torch
import torch.nn as nn
import torch.nn.functional as F
import onnx

print(torch.__version__)
print(onnx.__version__)


class TestModel(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self):
        super(TestModel, self).__init__()

    def forward(self, x):
        x = F.interpolate(x, scale_factor=2, mode='nearest')
        return x


torch_model = TestModel()
dummy_input = torch.randn(1, 3, 256, 256)

torch_out = torch.onnx.export(torch_model, dummy_input, 'model.onnx', verbose=True, opset_version=11)

onnx_model = onnx.load('model.onnx')
print(onnx_model)
onnx.checker.check_model(onnx_model)
```
